1. # **Abstract** {#abstract}

The aim of this work is to design and implement a 2D game engine specifically tailored for shooter games, providing developers with a flexible and efficient framework for creating dynamic games. This project involves constructing a modular engine architecture that supports essential components such as rendering, physics simulation, audio, and input handling. In addition, the engine will include an integrated entity–component system to facilitate efficient game object management and enable scalability for different shooter mechanics. The main objective is to offer a lightweight yet powerful platform that simplifies the development process while maintaining high performance and ease of customization. To demonstrate the engine’s capabilities, a prototype shooter game will be developed using the framework. The implementation will be carried out primarily in C++, utilizing libraries such as OpenGL for rendering and OpenAL for audio management.

2. # **Vocabulary** {#vocabulary}

**Game Engine** \-  is a software framework designed to provide the foundational systems and tools required to create and run video games. It separates core engine components such as rendering, physics etc. from game-specific content, including art assets, levels, and gameplay rules. This separation allows developers to reuse, extend, and modify the engine for multiple games without rewriting core systems. Game engines are typically designed to be extensible, supporting modular architectures, scripting, and genre-specific optimizations. While some engines are general-purpose, most are tailored for specific game genres or hardware, balancing flexibility with performance. The key feature that distinguishes a game engine from a standard game is its reusability and ability to serve as a foundation for developing multiple games with minimal modification \[1\].

**Shooter Game** \- is a video game genre where shooting mechanics are the primary means of interaction and progression, typically requiring players to aim and fire projectiles at targets or enemies to achieve objectives.

**OpenGL** \-  is an application programming interface (API) and software library that provides access to graphics hardware for rendering 2D and 3D graphics. It offers a streamlined, hardware-independent interface that can be implemented on various graphics systems or entirely in software. OpenGL includes commands for specifying geometric primitives, objects, images, and operations needed to create interactive graphics applications. However, it does not handle windowing, user input, or loading image files, which must be managed by separate libraries or the operating system. OpenGL is widely used in game development for rendering graphics efficiently across different platforms \[2\].

**Sprite** \- a small bitmap that can be overlaid on top of a full-screen background image without disrupting it, often drawn with the aid of specialized graphics hardware. In 2D game animation, sprites are used in sequences of frames to create the illusion of movement. These sequences, known as looping animations, make characters or objects appear to be performing actions such as running and walking \[1\].

**Collision Detection** \- a system in a game engine that determines whether objects in the game world have come into contact. Each object is represented by simple geometric shapes, and the system detects when these shapes intersect. Collision detection also provides information about contacts, which can be used to prevent visual glitches, support objects, trigger events, or simulate physical behaviors like bouncing and sliding \[1\].

**OpenAL \-**  is a cross-platform three-dimensional audio API. The API’s primary purpose is to allow an application to position audio sources in a three-dimensional space around a listener, producing reasonable spatialization of the sources for the audio system. OpenAL is appropriate for many audio applications, but was designed to be most appropriate for gaming audio \[3\].

**Entity–Component System (ECS) \-** is a software architectural pattern used in game development that organizes game objects into entities composed of modular components, which define their data and behavior in a flexible and efficient way \[4\].

3. # **Specification** {#specification}

   1. ## **Executive summary**   {#executive-summary}

The purpose of this project is to create a game engine that simplifies the process of building 2D shooter games. Many existing engines are either too complex for small scale projects or not optimized for the specific needs of shooter games. This work addresses that gap by providing an efficient, and easy to use solution for developers who want to develop games or experiment with gameplay mechanics. The engine provides the core features necessary for developing 2D shooter games and can be extended to support additional functionality in the future. The intended users are developers and students interested in game programming who seek a lightweight alternative to large commercial engines.

6. # **System Architecture** {#system-architecture}

The architecture of the developed 2D game engine follows a modular and layered design, where each subsystem is responsible for a specific aspect of the engine’s functionality. This approach promotes separation of concerns, scalability, and ease of maintenance, allowing each module to be developed, tested, and extended independently. The architecture consists of several interconnected nodes—modules—that collectively form the foundation of the engine. **Figure 3** presents the system architecture diagram of the 2D game engine.

## ![][image2]

**Figure 3: System Architecture Diagram**

## 

## **6.1 Architectural Overview** {#6.1-architectural-overview}

At the highest level, the engine is divided into three conceptual layers:

* **Core Layer:** Provides the essential systems and base infrastructure that all other modules depend on. This includes the Entity Component System (ECS), engine loop, time management, logging, and global coordination.

* **Subsystem Layer:** Contains independent modules responsible for handling specific domains such as rendering, physics, audio, input, and resource management. These modules interact with the Core Layer but remain loosely coupled to each other through well-defined interfaces.

* **Application Layer:** Represents the user-defined game logic built on top of the engine. It utilizes the services of the lower layers to create gameplay, scenes, and interactions. The Game Module belongs to this layer and demonstrates the integration of all engine systems.

 

## **6.2 Nodes and Responsibilities** {#6.2-nodes-and-responsibilities}

Each major module (or node) in the engine architecture has a specific role:

* **Core Module:** Manages the engine lifecycle, ECS framework, and communication between systems. It serves as the central coordinator that initializes and updates all other modules.

* **Rendering Module:** Handles all visual output using OpenGL, including sprite rendering, shader management, and camera transformations.

* **Physics Module:** Integrates Box2D to simulate realistic 2D physical interactions, including movement, collisions, and gravity.

* **Audio Module:** Utilizes OpenAL for 2D sound playback and spatial audio effects, managing sound sources and listeners.

* **Input Module:** Captures and processes keyboard and mouse events through GLFW, translating them into actionable game inputs.

* **Resource Management Module:** Oversees loading, caching, and unloading of assets such as textures, audio files, and configuration data to ensure efficient resource usage.

* **Interface Module:** Employs ImGui to provide debugging overlays and in-game tools for visualization and performance monitoring.

* **Game Module:** Implements the actual gameplay logic, scenes, and interactions by leveraging the engine’s subsystems.

## **6.3 Data and Control Flow** {#6.3-data-and-control-flow}

The engine follows a centralized update loop, controlled by the Core Module. During each frame:

1. **Input Handling:** The Input Module captures user input and updates the corresponding entity components.

2. **Physics Update:** The Physics Module computes motion, collisions, and physics interactions based on elapsed time.

3. **Game Logic:** The Game Module processes gameplay updates, entity states, and triggers interactions.

4. **Rendering:** The Rendering Module draws the current frame using the updated entity data.

5. **Audio Update:** The Audio Module synchronizes sound playback with in-game events and positions.

6. **Debugging and Interface:** The Interface Module renders diagnostic overlays and development tools if enabled.

7. # **Modules Design** {#modules-design}

The 2D game engine is implemented using a modular architecture, where each module exposes clear interfaces and communicates through the Entity Component System (ECS) and centralized engine core. This section details the internal design of each module, their interfaces, and the dependencies between layers.

## **7.1 Design Principles** {#7.1-design-principles}

The design of the modules follows three main principles:

* **Encapsulation:** Each module manages its own functionality and exposes only the necessary interfaces.

* **Loose Coupling:** Modules depend on abstractions rather than concrete implementations, enabling easy replacement or extension.

* **Layered Communication:** Data and control flow move from the **Core Layer** upward to the **Application Layer**, ensuring predictable system behavior.

## **7.2 Module Interfaces** {#7.2-module-interfaces}

Each module exposes a public interface to allow other parts of the engine or the game to interact with it:

* **Core Module Interface:** Provides lifecycle management functions such as `Init()`, `Update(float deltaTime)`, and `Shutdown()`. Other modules register themselves to the Core, which manages their update order and timing.

* **Rendering Module Interface:** Exposes rendering functions such as `RenderSprite()`, `LoadTexture()`, and `SetCamera()`. These are accessed by the Game Module and Resource Manager to draw scenes.

* **Physics Module Interface:** Offers methods like `AddBody()`, `ApplyForce()`, and `CheckCollision()`. It interacts with the ECS to synchronize entity transforms.

* **Audio Module Interface:** Provides functions such as `PlaySound()`, `SetListenerPosition()`, and `StopAll()`. It listens for events triggered by the Game Module.

* **Input Module Interface:** Defines callback-based or polling-based input functions, such as `IsKeyPressed()` and `GetMousePosition()`.

* **Resource Management Module Interface:** Exposes asset loading and caching functions like `LoadTexture()`, `GetAudio()`, and `UnloadAll()`. It is used by both the Rendering and Audio modules.

* **Interface Module Interface:** Provides methods to create and render debug overlays, such as `DrawWindow()`, `ShowPerformanceStats()`, and `EditEntityComponents()`.

* **Game Module Interface:** Contains the main game loop functions, level initialization routines, and entity registration with the ECS. It depends on nearly all other subsystems.

## **7.3 Dependencies Between Modules** {#7.3-dependencies-between-modules}

The dependencies between modules are intentionally designed to be unidirectional, reducing coupling and promoting maintainability.

* The **Core Module** is at the center, coordinating all others.

* The **Subsystem Layer** modules (Rendering, Physics, Audio, Input, Resource Management) depend on the **Core** for timing and lifecycle control.

* The **Game Module** depends on all subsystem modules to access engine functionalities.

* The **Interface Module** depends on the Core and Rendering modules to display runtime data and debug information.

There are no cyclic dependencies, modules do not depend on each other directly but communicate through the Core or shared ECS data.

8. # **Communication** {#communication}

The communication infrastructure of the 2D game engine defines how internal modules exchange data, handle input/output, and interact with external systems such as the operating system and graphics/audio APIs.

## **8.1 Communication Protocols** {#8.1-communication-protocols}

The engine primarily relies on **in-process communication** through a centralized **Entity Component System (ECS)** and the **Core Module**, which act as mediators between subsystems.  
 Key internal communication mechanisms include:

* **ECS Messaging:** Components and systems communicate indirectly through shared entities managed by the ECS. This decouples systems and eliminates the need for direct dependencies.

* **Event Dispatching:** A lightweight event system propagates real-time updates such as input events, collisions, and audio triggers. Events are queued and processed sequentially during the engine’s update cycle to ensure deterministic execution.

* **Callback Mechanisms:** Input handling and UI interactions rely on callbacks registered with the Input and Interface modules. These callbacks allow user-defined logic to respond to keyboard, mouse, or GUI events efficiently.

## **8.2 Communication Libraries** {#8.2-communication-libraries}

The engine employs several libraries to facilitate communication between hardware and software layers:

* **GLFW:** Handles window management, OpenGL context creation, and input event polling. It serves as the primary interface between the engine and the operating system, enabling the capture of keyboard and mouse inputs.

* **OpenGL:** Provides the graphics rendering interface used by the Rendering Module. Communication between the CPU and GPU occurs via OpenGL API calls for vertex data, shader programs, and texture management.

* **OpenAL:** Manages communication with the audio hardware for sound playback. The Audio Module interacts with OpenAL to control sound sources, buffers, and listener properties.

Each of these libraries operates at a different layer, but all communicate through the Core Module to maintain synchronization and consistent timing.

9. # **Main Components Description** {#main-components-description}

## **9.1 Activity Diagram** {#9.1-activity-diagram}

The activity diagram shown in **Figure 4** illustrates the main execution flow of the 2D game engine, from initialization to shutdown. Upon launching the engine, the **Core Module** initializes all subsystems including Rendering, Physics, Audio, Input, and Resource Management.  
After initialization, the **Game Module** enters the main loop, continuously performing input processing, physics updates, game logic, and rendering until the application is closed. When the user exits the game, the engine sequentially shuts down all modules and releases resources.

![][image3]

**Figure 4: Activity Diagram**

## **9.2 Class Diagram** {#9.2-class-diagram}

**Figure 5** presents the unified class diagram of the 2D game engine, illustrating how the core architecture, subsystems, and entity-component-system (ECS) structure interact to support the execution of a shooter game. The diagram demonstrates the modular design of the engine, where each subsystem is responsible for a specific aspect of the game loop such as rendering, physics, input, audio, and resource management.

At the center of the architecture lies the **CoreModule**, which orchestrates the initialization, update, and shutdown phases of the engine. It manages the **ECS**, responsible for maintaining entities, components, and systems that define the game world. Each **Entity** serves as an identifier that aggregates multiple **Components**, which store data such as position, texture, or physics attributes. The **Systems** operate on these components to implement behaviors, for example, updating physics or rendering visible objects.

The **RenderingModule**, **PhysicsModule**, **AudioModule**, and **InputModule** form the primary subsystems of the engine, each managed by their corresponding system classes (**RenderSystem**, **PhysicsSystem**, **AudioSystem**, and **InputSystem**). These systems communicate with the ECS to retrieve and modify entity data during each update cycle. The **ResourceManager** handles asset loading, such as textures and sounds, ensuring efficient memory use, while the **InterfaceModule** provides in-game and debugging interfaces using tools like Dear ImGui.

Finally, the **GameModule** integrates all subsystems to implement gameplay logic, level initialization, and scene updates. It leverages the engine’s modular design to manage player behavior, enemy interactions, and overall game flow. This architecture promotes scalability, maintainability, and reusability, allowing new features and components to be easily integrated without disrupting the core engine structure.

**Figure 5: Class Diagram**

10. # **External Interfaces** {#external-interfaces}

## **10.1 File Formats** {#10.1-file-formats}

The engine supports a variety of standardized file formats for assets, configuration, and scene data to ensure compatibility with common content creation tools.

* **Texture Files:**  
  Supported formats include `.png`, `.jpg`, and `.bmp`, which are loaded via the *stb\_image* library and converted into OpenGL-compatible textures.

* **Audio Files:**  
  The engine supports `.wav` files for background music and sound effects, decoded using OpenAL-compatible loaders.

* **Shader Files:**  
  Shaders are written in GLSL (`.vert`, `.frag`) and loaded as plain text files by the Rendering Module, adhering to OpenGL shader pipeline conventions.

* **Configuration Files:**  
  Engine and game configurations are stored in `.json` format for readability and easy modification. These define settings such as screen resolution, volume levels, and control bindings.

* **Scene or Level Data:**  
  Scene information can be exported in `.json` or custom text-based formats, allowing flexibility in defining entity placement, physics parameters, and game logic bindings.

11. # **Technology Selection** {#technology-selection}

This section provides an overview of the technologies and libraries used in the design and implementation of the 2D game engine for shooter games.

## **11.1 C++** {#11.1-c++}

C++ was selected as the primary programming language due to its strong performance, low-level memory control, and widespread use in game engine development. Its object-oriented nature and support for modular programming make it ideal for building complex, real-time systems like rendering pipelines, physics engines, and asset managers. The engine is developed using the **C++17 standard.** 

## **11.2 OpenGL (v4.6 Core Profile)** {#11.2-opengl-(v4.6-core-profile)}

OpenGL (Open Graphics Library) is a cross-platform graphics API that provides access to the GPU for rendering 2D and 3D graphics \[2\]. It allows developers to define geometric primitives, apply transformations, and manage textures and shaders to create visually engaging scenes. In this project, OpenGL is utilized for rendering 2D sprites, handling textures, and managing the graphics pipeline. Its portability and hardware abstraction make it a reliable choice for ensuring consistent visual performance across different devices.

## **11.3 GLFW (v3.4)** {#11.3-glfw-(v3.4)}

GLFW is a lightweight, open-source library used for creating windows, managing OpenGL contexts, and handling input such as keyboard, mouse, and game controllers \[5\]. It simplifies the window creation and event management process, enabling a streamlined setup for rendering using OpenGL. In this project, GLFW provides the foundation for window and input handling.

## **11.4 GLAD (v0.1.36)** {#11.4-glad-(v0.1.36)}

GLAD is an OpenGL loader library that manages OpenGL function pointers at runtime \[6\]. It ensures compatibility with different versions of OpenGL and simplifies the process of accessing modern graphics functionality. In this project, GLAD is used to initialize and manage the OpenGL function pointers required by the rendering system.

## **11.5 OpenAL (v1.1)** {#11.5-openal-(v1.1)}

OpenAL (Open Audio Library) is a cross-platform 3D audio API designed for rendering spatial sound \[3\]. It enables applications to position audio sources within a three-dimensional environment, enhancing immersion by simulating realistic sound propagation. In this project, OpenAL is used to manage sound effects such as gunfire, explosions, and ambient background sounds, enriching the overall gameplay experience with spatialized audio cues.

## 

## **11.6 stb\_image (v2.28)** {#11.6-stb_image-(v2.28)}

The stb\_image library is a lightweight, single-header image loading library used to read image files such as PNG, JPG, and BMP \[7\]. It simplifies the texture-loading process by converting image data into formats suitable for OpenGL texture creation. Within the game engine, stb\_image is responsible for loading sprite textures and graphical assets used in rendering 2D environments and characters.

## **11.7 Box2D (v2.4.1)** {#11.7-box2d-(v2.4.1)}

Box2D is a 2D physics engine that simulates rigid body dynamics, collisions, and physical interactions between objects. It provides realistic behavior for entities such as projectiles, walls, and player characters \[8\]. In this project, Box2D is integrated into the engine to manage collision detection, gravity, and responses between game entities, ensuring consistent and realistic physics simulation during gameplay.

## **11.8 spdlog  (v1.13.0)** {#11.8-spdlog-(v1.13.0)}

spdlog is a high-performance, header-only logging library for C++. It provides fast, thread-safe logging with customizable output formats and sink options, such as console, file, or rotating logs \[9\]. In this project, spdlog is used to record runtime information, error messages, and performance data.

## **11.9 ImGui (v1.91.0)** {#11.9-imgui-(v1.91.0)}

Dear ImGui is a graphical user interface library designed for creating real-time development tools and overlays. It provides an immediate mode GUI that enables developers to build interactive panels for debugging, visualization, and parameter adjustment \[10\]. In this project, ImGui is used to implement runtime interfaces such as performance monitors, configuration menus, and diagnostic tools.

## **11.10 EnTT (v3.13.2)** {#11.10-entt-(v3.13.2)}

EnTT is a fast and lightweight entity component system (ECS) library for C++ that simplifies game object management and improves runtime efficiency. It decouples game entities from their data and behavior, promoting flexibility and scalability in engine design \[11\]. In this project, EnTT is used to manage entities such as players, bullets, and environmental objects.

## **11.11 CMake (v3.31)** {#11.11-cmake-(v3.31)}

CMake is a cross-platform build system generator used to automate compilation, linking, and dependency management \[12\]. It simplifies project configuration and ensures consistent builds across operating systems and compilers. In this project, CMake is used to manage the compilation process of all engine modules, link third-party libraries such as OpenGL, Box2D, etc., and streamline integration across development environments.

## 

## **11.12 Windows 10/11 (64-bit)** {#11.12-windows-10/11-(64-bit)}

The engine is developed and tested primarily on **Windows 10 and Windows 11 (64-bit)** systems. This platform was chosen due to its widespread use, comprehensive development tool support (such as Visual Studio and CMake integration), and reliable driver compatibility for OpenGL and OpenAL.
